  "footnotes": [
    "Ghana Empire (c.300–1235): not located in modern Ghana but in southeastern Mauritania and western Mali; the Soninke empire controlled trans-Saharan gold-salt trade routes; its capital Kumbi Saleh may have housed 30,000 people; Almoravid pressure and internal fragmentation led to its decline, succeeded by the Mali Empire",
    "Mali Empire (c.1235–1600): founded by Sundiata Keita after defeating the Sosso at the Battle of Kirina; Mansa Musa's pilgrimage to Mecca (1324) distributed so much gold that he depressed gold prices in Egypt for a decade; Timbuktu and Djenné became centers of Islamic learning with the University of Sankore reportedly housing 25,000 students",
    "Songhai Empire (c.1430–1591): the largest empire in African history by area, centered on the Niger River city of Gao; Askia Muhammad (r.1493–1528) organized it into provinces with a professional bureaucracy; its destruction by a Moroccan Saadi expedition armed with firearms (Battle of Tondibi, 1591) ended the era of great Sahelian empires",
    "Sokoto Caliphate (1804–1903): founded by Usman dan Fodio's Fulani jihad against the Hausa city-states, it was the largest state in 19th-century Africa with perhaps 10 million subjects; it reformed Islamic practice, expanded education, and created a federal system of emirates; the British conquered it in 1903 but preserved its emirate structure through indirect rule",
    "Ashanti Empire (c.1670–1902): the Akan-speaking Ashanti built a powerful centralized state in the Gold Coast (modern Ghana), united by the Golden Stool (Sika Dwa Kofi); they fought four wars against the British before annexation in 1902; the Ashanti king (Asantehene) remains culturally significant today",
    "Trans-Saharan trade: for over a millennium, camel caravans carried gold, salt, slaves, and luxury goods between West Africa and the Mediterranean; this trade created the wealth of Ghana, Mali, and Songhai; the shift to Atlantic maritime trade (Portuguese from the 1440s) gradually reoriented West African economies coastward",
    "Scramble for Africa in West Africa: France dominated the interior (French West Africa covered 4.7 million km²), while Britain controlled the most economically valuable coastal territories (Nigeria, Gold Coast, Sierra Leone); the Berlin Conference (1884–85) formalized partition; independence came mostly in 1960, the 'Year of Africa'"
  ]
}
